title: For Sale:  Smith and Wesson DA Revolver
location: Santa Fe, NM, New Mexico, United States
postcontent:
This revolver was made in the 1920s, but it shoots and locks up as tight as a new one. Pre-war craftsmanship through and through. I wish Smith still made them like this. It is a S&W Hand Ejector .32. It is built on the "I" Frame which is just slightly smaller than the current "J" frames like the Chiefs Special. This one is nice because it has the longer 4.25 inch barrel. This looks like a long barrel on this gun, doesn't it? It's actually quite small and really cool. Al Capone would have liked it and so will you.  

It has a nice and tight action, and locks up and is as smooth as new. Bore is bright and shiny but with a few scattered spots in it. I have shot this revolver and it is a good one, and quite accurate. Finish has a lot of mixed blue and gray, but a very smooth patina and not pitted at all. Only 80 years of careful use can get this finish. Grips are perfect. Serial number is 95704 which puts it as being made in the 1920s, I believe. I have 34 rounds of ammunition that will go with it, so you will be ready to go when you buy it. 

These old S&Ws are quality pieces, and this would not only be a good investment, it would also make a fine concealed carry gun, trial gun, or just a fun plinker. Price is $275, which will get you something nice like this, or a plastic gun that won't exactly ever be a family heirloom. 

This S&W has not been shot much in its long history. This isn't some loose, rusty, or reblued junker. It's a nice revolver and you will like it when you see it.

Contact me through Armslist with your phone number and I will call you to arrange to meet. I sold a similar one a couple of days ago very quickly so if you missed that one, shoot the email out to me quickly. This one is even better than the nickeled one from 2 days ago. It has its original finish and grips.

Increase in federal excise tax on handguns (both pistols and revolvers) from 11% - 20%

The Nagant M1895 Revolver is a seven-shot, gas-seal revolver designed and produced by Belgian industrialist Léon Nagant for the Russian Empire. The Nagant M1895 was chambered for a proprietary cartridge, 7.62x38R, and featured an unusual "gas-seal" system, in which the cylinder moved forward when the gun was cocked, to close the gap between the cylinder and the barrel, providing a boost to the muzzle velocity of the fired projectile and allowing the weapon to be suppressed (an unusual ability for a revolver).[3] Other Nagant revolver designs were also adopted by police and military services of Sweden (7.5 mm M1887), Norway (M1893), Poland, and Greece (Περίστροφον M1895). These revolvers were largely similar to the Russian Nagant M1895, but lacked the gas seal mechanism.

postcontent:
The 3MR is a drop-in 3-mode fire control system with Safe, Semi-Automatic, and Tac-Con™’s patented 3rd Mode. The 3rd mode has a positive reset that dramatically reduces the split times between shots. The positive reset characteristic is achieved by transferring the force from the bolt carrier through the trigger assembly to assist the trigger back onto the front sear. As a result, this gives the firearm the fastest reset possible. Both semi and 3rd mode positions exhibit a non-adjustable 4.5 pound trigger pull weight.
Listers basic review of this product : This tigger is designed for those who want a high rate of fire but want to control their shots for maximum efffectivenes.  This trigger has a small learning curve to master but will fire at rate close to a full auto with more control for more shots on target.  If you want to just dump magazines as fast as you can (spray and pray) this is not for you.  This trigger is very crisp. I had 4 other people try this out at the range and they had a blast.
